{"title_page": "Jeremy Rogers Limited", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Jeremy Rogers Limited\n| logo             = Jeremy Rogers Limited logo 2012.jpg\n| logo_size        = 250px\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Limited company]]\n| traded_as        = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = 1961\n| founder          = [[Jeremy Rogers]]\n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city    = [[Lymington]], [[Hampshire]]\n| location_country = [[UK]]\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = Kit Rogers\n| industry         = Yacht building\n| products         = \n| production       = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|www.jeremyrogers.co.uk}}\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Jeremy Rogers Ltd.''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] boatyard based in [[Lymington]]. Founded by English boatbuilder and sailor [[Jeremy Rogers]] in 1961, it is currently known for construction to order of the classic [[Contessa 32]] design, and refurbishment of Contessa and other yachts. The yard is notable for the high quality handbuilding of the yachts, and the renownd [[seaworthiness]] of the designs compared to modern mass-production yards.\n\n==History==\n\nThe business was founded by Rogers in 1961, and by the early 1980s was employing 200 people in five factories in Lymington building the [[Contessa 26]], [[Contessa 32]] and the Doug Peterson designed Grand Prix 35s, 39s and 43s, and exporting the yachts worldwide. Although an insolvency forced production to stop, in 1995 the Contessa 32 moulds were bought back and production on a bespoke basis restarted. The yard currently offers refurbishment and parts support for Contessa yachts, as well as refitting of other yacht makes.\n\n===A 'Green' Contessa===\n[[File:Contessa 32 Cabin 1.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Saloon and galley of ''Calypso'', showing the Kebony joinery.]]\n2011, the 40th Anniversary of the Contessa 32, saw a renewed interest in new Contessa 32s after Rogers exhibited his new \"greener\" Contessa 32 ''Calypso'' at the [[Southampton Boat Show]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeremy Rogers - Contessa 32|url=http://www.southamptonboatshow.com/2011/visiting/exhibitor_list/exhibitor_profile.aspx?objectid=16559|work=Exhibitor Profiles|publisher=Southampton Boat Show|accessdate=9 June 2012}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  in collaboration with The Green Blue (a collaborative effort of the [[Royal Yachting Association]] and the [[British Marine Federation]]).<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thegreenblue.org.uk/news/latest_news/2010/calypso_is_launched.aspx\n|title=The Green Blue and Jeremy Rogers Ltd Launch Calypso - a 'greener' Contessa 32\n|date=13 September 2010\n|accessdate=31 January 2011\n|publisher=The Green Blue\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924171440/http://www.thegreenblue.org.uk/news/latest_news/2010/calypso_is_launched.aspx\n|archive-date=24 September 2010\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref> ''Calypso'' showcased a variety of sustainable products and technology. \n\nThe deck and interior woodwork is made from sustainable '[[Kebony|Kebonised]]' maple rather than unsustainable tropical hardwoods such as [[teak]] and [[mahogany]]. A diesel-electric [[Hybrid vehicle|hybrid]] Beta 25 engine is used to lower fuel consumption, and a solar panel and wind generator are fitted.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rogers|first=Jessie|title=A Contessa 32 for our times|url=http://www.kebony.no/docs/nyhetsvedlegg/20100609_pbo.pdf|publisher=Practical Boat Owner|accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>  The deck is glued with Saba adhesive, which is solvent-free and unlike the more commonly used Sikaflex does not contain [[isocyanate]]s which are linked to asthma and cancer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Compton|first=Nic|title=Green Machine|url=http://www.sailingmagazine.net/news/features/1007-green-machine|publisher=Sailing Magazine|accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref> [[Linseed]]-based [[petrochemical]]-free Le Tonkinois varnish is used for the wood, and the hull is painted with Hempasil non-toxic [[antifouling|antifoul]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of sailboat designers and manufacturers]]\n*[[Contessa 26]]\n*[[Contessa 32]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jeremyrogers.co.uk/ Jeremy Rogers Limited]\n\n[[Category:British boat builders]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1961]]\n[[Category:English brands]]\n[[Category:Yacht building companies]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Jeremy Rogers Limited\n| logo             = Jeremy Rogers Limited logo 2012.jpg\n| logo_size        = 250px\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Limited company]]\n| traded_as        = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = 1961\n| founder          = [[Jeremy Rogers]]\n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city    = [[Lymington]], [[Hampshire]]\n| location_country = [[UK]]\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = Kit Rogers\n| industry         = Yacht building\n| products         = \n| production       = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|www.jeremyrogers.co.uk}}\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Jeremy Rogers Ltd.''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] boatyard based in [[Lymington]]. Founded by English boatbilder and sailor [[Jeremy Rogers]] in 1961, it is currently known for construction to order of the classic [[Contessa 32]] design, and refurbishment of Contessa and other yachts. The yard is notable for the high quality handbuilding of the yachts, and the renownd [[seaworthiness]] of the designs compared to modern mass-production yards.\n\n==History==\n\nThe business was founded by Rogers in 1961, and by the early 1980s was employing 200 people in five factories in Lymington building the [[Contessa 26]], [[Contessa 32]] and the Doug Peterson designed Grand Prix 35s, 39s and 43s, and exporting the yachts worldwide. Although an insolvency forced production to stop, in 1995 the Contessa 32 moulds were bought back and production on a bespoke basis restarted. The yard currently offers refurbishment and parts support for Contessa yachts, as well as refitting of other yacht makes.\n\n===A 'Green' Contessa===\n[[File:Contessa 32 Cabin 1.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Saloon and galley of ''Calypso'', showing the Kebony joinery.]]\n2011, the 40th Anniversary of the Contessa 32, saw a renewed interest in new Contessa 32s after Rogers exhibited his new \"greener\" Contessa 32 ''Calypso'' at the [[Southampton Boat Show]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeremy Rogers - Contessa 32|url=http://www.southamptonboatshow.com/2011/visiting/exhibitor_list/exhibitor_profile.aspx?objectid=16559|work=Exhibitor Profiles|publisher=Southampton Boat Show|accessdate=9 June 2012}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  in collaboration with The Green Blue (a collaborative effort of the [[Royal Yachting Association]] and the [[British Marine Federation]]).<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thegreenblue.org.uk/news/latest_news/2010/calypso_is_launched.aspx\n|title=The Green Blue and Jeremy Rogers Ltd Launch Calypso - a 'greener' Contessa 32\n|date=13 September 2010\n|accessdate=31 January 2011\n|publisher=The Green Blue\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924171440/http://www.thegreenblue.org.uk/news/latest_news/2010/calypso_is_launched.aspx\n|archive-date=24 September 2010\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref> ''Calypso'' showcased a variety of sustainable products and technology. \n\nThe deck and interior woodwork is made from sustainable '[[Kebony|Kebonised]]' maple rather than unsustainable tropical hardwoods such as [[teak]] and [[mahogany]]. A diesel-electric [[Hybrid vehicle|hybrid]] Beta 25 engine is used to lower fuel consumption, and a solar panel and wind generator are fitted.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rogers|first=Jessie|title=A Contessa 32 for our times|url=http://www.kebony.no/docs/nyhetsvedlegg/20100609_pbo.pdf|publisher=Practical Boat Owner|accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>  The deck is glued with Saba adhesive, which is solvent-free and unlike the more commonly used Sikaflex does not contain [[isocyanate]]s which are linked to asthma and cancer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Compton|first=Nic|title=Green Machine|url=http://www.sailingmagazine.net/news/features/1007-green-machine|publisher=Sailing Magazine|accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref> [[Linseed]]-based [[petrochemical]]-free Le Tonkinois varnish is used for the wood, and the hull is painted with Hempasil non-toxic [[antifouling|antifoul]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of sailboat designers and manufacturers]]\n*[[Contessa 26]]\n*[[Contessa 32]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jeremyrogers.co.uk/ Jeremy Rogers Limited]\n\n[[Category:British boat builders]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1961]]\n[[Category:English brands]]\n[[Category:Yacht building companies]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Croakingtoad", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected spelling error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeremy_Rogers_Limited"}
